rcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0149"><gtr:id>F0B3AC46-A59F-4D63-ABC0-E2010F635656</gtr:id><gtr:title>International Comparisons in Public Participation in Culture &amp;amp; Sport</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0149</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>There is policy interest in the levels of public participation in culture and sport with respect both to the issue of value for money for the public purse, and to whether levels of participation are similar in different groups in society.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In England there is an increasing amount of research about participation (both active and receptive) in culture and sport, including details of the activities engaged in, motivations and barriers, previous life experiences of participants and the demographic, socio-economic and cultural background of respondents. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Studies also exist for a number of other countries, which vary both in how the data are collected/questions are asked, and the way in which culture and sport, and the nature of the enquiry, are framed. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The purpose of this project is to update and expand previous mapping of participation studies internationally, and to explore the extent to which they might be comparable, and able to identify actual differences in levels of participation. In addition, the project will explore the availability of contextual data, such as spend on culture and sport, and the provision of cultural and sporting facilities, as understanding each country's context is critical to meaningful international comparisons. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-08-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>16252</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-173-27-0149</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-173-27-0149</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>B57EEFB7-602E-4F5D-92E4-A0C265266249</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Demography &amp; human geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>3A4CB57C-9B22-41A2-AB15-127503299365</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Human Geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></